<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>ADF0052</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="98" height="98" alt="" style="margin-left:0pt; margin-top:0pt; position:absolute; z-index:-65536" /></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ADF0052</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sylvie Sklan</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.00</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Introdu</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ction and background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.01</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has provided a unique opportunity to establish publicly funded schools that offer the Steiner curriculum. We believe that the expansion of Steiner provision under the academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would be a good thing. We have evidence of significant national demand from parents for the creation of further Steiner Academies. We also have emergent evidence that Steiner Academies are ‘narrowing the gap’ through an approach that starts formal learning later, yet enables their students to achieve excellent outcomes over a broad range of competencies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.02</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When Ministers agreed to establish a first Steiner academy in the very early days of the academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, this represented a radical and progressive step. It came about as a result of our successful lobbying effort to find a way to publicly fund schools that offer a curriculum other than the national curriculum.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It required Ministers to make several radical exceptions to the norm, in particular the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disapplication</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the national curriculum, but also exemption from KS1 SATs, QTS and teacher pay and conditions. Subsequently the removal of these requirements has become the norm, although this is now under review.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">These flexibilities remain key to allowing more diverse provision, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">irrespective of whether flexibilities are achieved through deregulation or through effective systems for allowing for exceptions to a more regulated framework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.03</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Steiner academies are still a very small part of the academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The Steiner Academy Hereford (SAH) was the first publicly funded Steiner school in the UK. It was established in 2008as a conversion from an independent school.    It is an all-though academy to 16 with capacity for 330 pupils. From the outset about one third of pupils have been on the academy’s SEN register. Also from the outset demand has outstripped supply with the academy having to hold waiting lists for all its year groups.  In 2011 the Steiner Academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Frome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (SAF) was opened, with places for young children only, but with a plan to grow to become an all-through academy from 4-16 with 624 places by 2020. In Sept 2012 another Steiner academy opened in Exeter, with similar limited provision to begin with and a plan to grow to offer two-form entry from 4 - 16.  A fourth Steiner academy is due to open in Bristol next September. The level of parental demand for a place in the Steiner Academies is high and so far the evidence is that demand outstrips supply.  Demand data for Steiner Academies that are being proposed also are significantly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">high.Given</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that there is concern that some approved Free Schools proposals are not able to match their demand survey with an ability to fill all their places when they open, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">it should be noted that demand for Steiner education seems to translate into a new Steiner Academy being able to fill its places as soon as it opens. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.04</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The supply of suitably qualified teachers and leaders is a challenge for us. We are working with higher education providers to develop new teacher training routes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SAH is registered as a School Direct provider, partnered with Worcester University. Canterbury University offers a Masters in Steiner Education and the University of the West of England is now offering a Steiner education specialism within its existing B Ed degree course.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.00</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The effectiveness of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.01</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’ of provision that previously was available only outside the mainstream clearly increases parental choice and makes available a different route to successful outcomes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In its recent OFSTED report (July 2013) the Steiner Academy Hereford (SAH)was deemed to be a good school, with the Inspector’s report stating:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This is a good school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”… “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Teachers have excellent relationships with pupils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”… “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Pupils are happy and have a great enjoyment of learning.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Pupils achieve well throughout the school, reaching above the expected levels in English and mathematics and in the other subjects that they take in Year 11”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Pupils who have disabilities and those who have special educational needs also make good and sometimes outstanding progress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Pupils’ artistic and practical achievements are impressive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and are reflected in older students’ high grades in their GCSE work and their excellent singing and drama.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Older students develop strong independent working and thinking skills… [and]… go on to successfully study and achieve wide ranging qualifications at GCE A level and beyond.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Pupils develop a very high degree of regard for others and of self-awareness”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Older pupils look after each other and have great empathy for others’ points of view.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he latest GCSE results from SAH show 80% of the students gained the expected benchmark % GCSEs at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A* - C including English and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">maths</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with over half doing so at Grades A/A*. These results are substantially above national averages (67%). Students in receipt of Pupil Premium did as well as their peers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.02</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Emergent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">findings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on data from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SAH,show</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the Steiner approach is successfully narrowing the gap for disadvantaged pupils.  Data show that pupils make significant improvements in their cognitive abilities between Year 7 – 9 as measured by CATs when compared to pupils in other schools. The improvements are similar to improvements achieved through specific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which focus on cognitive acceleration and the development of thinking skills (such as CASE, P4C and others).  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">SEN pupils show a particular improvement and pupils in receipt of targeted funding (Pupil Premium) made progress equal to their peers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Also, when compared to pupils in other schools, SAH pupils, including those on the SEN register and FSM pupils, significantly exceed the CATs predictors of their GCSE performance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.03</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is evidence from other sources that the Steiner curriculum may support cognitive acceleration, including the following:  socially disadvantaged pupils in Steiner schools do better than comparable students in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">neighbouring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> schools (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Schieffer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Busse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, 2001, McDermott 1996, Byers et al 1996); non-gifted Steiner students showed characteristics of the creative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of gifted students in other schools (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Hutchingson</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Hutchingson,1993); scientific reasoning of Steiner school students was found to be superior to their mainstream counterparts (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Jelinek</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Sun, 2003) </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.04</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The fact that demand for school transfer admissions is high indicates that parents </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">perceivethat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the Steiner approach is able to reach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> children who are not flourishing in standard model schools. There is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">high volume of admission inquiries at SAH and SAF for school transfers throughout the school year from parents who say that they want their child to be educated at the Steiner Academy because their child is not flourishing in their current school. Hence the waiting lists for all year groups.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.05</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that schools which are delivering an innovative or non-mainstream curriculum and educational practices should maximise the contribution that they make to the general raising of standards by participating in research, evaluation and sharing of practice, and that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">they should be supported in this by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">developmentof</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> appropriate national programmes for collaborative research and development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.00</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a bigger contribution from the Steiner approach? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.01</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have evidence of significant national demand from parents for the creation of further Steiner Academies. We also have evidence of considerable interest and support for the development of the Steiner Academies from teachers and senior leadership staff currently working within mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">education.However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, any expansion will rely on retaining and refining the flexibilities that we negotiated for the first Steiner Academy as listed in para 1.02 above.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.02</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Other suggested steps to support expansion:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Steiner academies are exempt from the requirement to sit statutory assessments at Key Stage 1 in recognition that the formal teaching of literacy and numeracy are introduced later. The earlier the stage of the curriculum the greater the divergent from the national curriculum.   KS2 SATs are required and results have been well below national average in SAH, particularly in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mathematics,because</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the school’s programme does not mirror the national curriculum. The KS2 SATs therefore do not give an accurate indication of final educational outcomes or any useful measure of pupil progress and are thus misleading for both parents and teaching staff. This can be clearly seen from the pattern of low achievement within KS2 SATs and high achievement at GCSE level for pupils at SAH.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The introduction of more flexibility to disaggregation of national assessment requirements from the national curriculum; the introduction of a clause in the Funding Agreement that states that pupils are following the Steiner curriculum</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The current inspection framework places emphasis on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">comparative progress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(i.e. with other schools and national averages for a range of pupil groups) in coming to judgements about whether a school is ‘good enough’.  This poses a risk of an unfair judgment for a newly established Steiner Academy that has younger pupils only, because the Steiner expectations for younger pupils diverge significantly from national expectations.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We would like to see           a) greater weight in Ofsted inspections being given to a school’s own systems for assessing pupil progress; b) for adjustments to be made to the inspection framework to compare like with like; c)more flexibilities regarding national expectation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Restrictions of one kind or another influence the smallness of the size of  some academies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It would be good to have a mechanism in place that can address diseconomy of scale where the small size of an academy is inevitable, such as in an academy serving a rural area in which a larger school would compel undesirably long journeys for pupils.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.00</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.01</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Existing independent Steiner schools have ended up in the private sector because historically there has been nowhere else for them to go.  They have struggled there and are not well resourced. However, with the investment of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">properresources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, an existing Steiner school would have the potential to deliver immediate state-funded provision across a full range of year groups, rather than opening with only small range as is the case for most new Academies.  Also, Steiner schools historically have developed an extremely high level of commitment and engagement among parents. Bringing this culture of parental engagement and commitment into the state sector could have significant effects on pupil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">achievement.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> would like to suggest more flexible prerequisites for cash-poor, experience-rich private schools wishing to convert to an academy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.03</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Steiner Academies sector is still emerging and is developing its framework of policy and practice. To </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dateSteiner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Academies have been created by independent groups, working within an informal framework of quality assurance supported by the Steiner Waldorf Schools Fellowship. The recognition that the resources of the SWSF (and other small charities) as a sponsor are very limited.  However, we want to develop a more consistent and transparent framework of standards and quality assurance for state-funded Steiner education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.00</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.01</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Parents perceive Steiner academies as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">offeringa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> caring and gentle environment that would be highly appropriate for children with SEN. As a result, Steiner Academies cannot meet the current level of demand that exists from parents who wish to name a Steiner Academy in a statement of SEN. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For us, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">akey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> point of interdependency with the LA that could be improved is the process for naming of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">theAcademy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in a statement of SEN. As an Academy, the school has the right to challenge the naming of the school </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">where admitting the child would be incompatible with the provision of efficient education for other children and where no reasonable steps may be made to secure compatibility (Annex 3 of the FA).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If an Academy does not consent to be named on a Statement of SEN, and the LA disagrees, the LA should not go ahead and name the Academy regardless. However, this does not always happen. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Systems need to be tightened </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">upto</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> prevent a LA naming an academy where the academy has not consented.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.02</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In a landscape of increasing diversity in educational provision, it might also be appropriate to consider a higher level of engagement between local authorities and individual schools, to map out the capacity and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">specialisms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of schools across a local authority area in terms of fair access </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">andmeeting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the needs of children with statements of SEN in a more coherent, ‘joined-up’ way.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.00</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.01</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that the Steiner academies have a valuable role to play in the new school landscape, and we feel that working together as a chain of schools could significantly improve our ability to deliver consistently excellent Steiner education. We have a vision for how the Steiner Academies might work together as a chain of schools to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">providequality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> control, collective training, curriculum development, assessment systems, procurement, etc.  This will reinforce our common purpose and strengthen our capacity to contribute to the over-all education landscape and the sharing of best practice; it will also generate significant economies of scale, enabling a higher proportion of funding to be spent directly on education, helping to raise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">standards.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> availability of grant funding to support groups of existing academies in forming multi-academy trusts would help to roll out the benefits of collaboration and federation between academies more rapidly.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.02</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have no objection in principle to these chains being accountable through an appropriate inspection regime. Where schools are working to innovative or non-standard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">curriculums,there</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> could be significant benefits for both schools and those tasked with their inspection if such schools operated as chains within MATs or other models of federation, in that appropriate systems for assessing and evaluating pupil progress could be agreed with Ofsted and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> across the chain of schools. This would provide better accountability for non-standard schools on the delivery of their chosen outcomes.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.03</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our vision as a group of schools is for a relatively high level of delegation to individual schools, with an empowered and locally accountable governing body in each </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">school.We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> feel that transparency and accountability at a local (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> single school) level is essential for parental engagement and trust.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.00</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.01</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Steiner academies so far are all-though schools and therefore include primary provision. Currently a proposal is being prepared for Primary Steiner Academy.  If this proposal is approved then we would hope to be able to provide positive evidence regarding a Steiner primary academy contribution to primary provision locally.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.00</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">SUMMARY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Development of those flexibilities which are key to allowing more diverse provision </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Factoring that demand for Steiner education seems to translate into a new Steiner Academy being able to fill its places as soon as it opens when considering proposals further Steiner Academy </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Support for the development of appropriate national programmes for collaborative educational development </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">isaggregation of national assessment requirements from the national curriculum </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The introduction of a clause in the Funding Agreement that states that pupils are following the Steiner curriculum</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Giving greater weight in Ofsted inspections to a school’s own systems for assessing pupil progress</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Adjustments to the inspection framework to compare like with like</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More flexibilities regarding national expectations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A financial mechanism to address diseconomy of scale where the small size of an academy is inevitable</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More flexible prerequisites for cash-poor, experience-rich private schools wishing to convert to an academy </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tightened up systems to prevent a LA naming an academy in a statement of SEN where the academy has not consented</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The availability of grant funding to support groups of existing academies in forming multi-academy trusts.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>